<DOC><DOCNO> AP880901-0256 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0143EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-01 0495</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0517</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Education Department may be paying banksand other lenders millions of dollars each year in excess subsidieson student loans, a congressional watchdog agency says.   The General Accounting Office said Wednesday its auditors whoreviewed 2,038 loan accounts at 16 major lenders found 18 percentwere in error or lacked adequate documentation to support theamount billed.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cordis Corp. has pleaded guilty in federal court toconcealing defects in thousands of heart pacemakers, and fourformer executives were indicted for allegedly trying to cover upthe problems.   The problems affected thousands of pacemakers sold from 1980 to1985, according to Wednesday's indictment, which gave no precisefigures.   Assistant Attorney General John R. Bolton, head of the JusticeDepartment's civil division in Washington, and interim Miami U.S.Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, called the case ``the most significantfelony prosecution to date'' under the 1976 Medical DeviceAmendments to the FDA law.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil companies have submitted 371 bidstotaling more than $190 million in an effort to grab bargain-pricedleases on 270 tracts of government-owend offshore properties in thewestern Gulf of Mexico.   The high bids ran to more than $131 million. Sohio Petroleum Co.had the highest bid of the day with a $7.5 million offer for atract in the High Island area off the Texas-Louisiana coast. Thebid came to $1,306.24 per acre.   It was the second offering of government-owned tracts in thewestern gulf and the third gulf lease sale since the InteriorDepartment dropped the minimum per-acre price on the property from$150 to $25.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The National Labor Relations Board is wideningthe door for unions to recruit millions of health care workers,telling hospitals they no longer can lump nurses with physicians,or lab technicians with janitors as a tactic for thwartingorganizing drives.   In a 153-page set of proposed regulations to be published today,the NLRB is establishing eight broad categories of hospitalemployees as appropriate separate bargaining units.   The Associated Press obtained a copy of the regulationsWednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal law guaranteeing customers of banks,savings associations and credit unions timely access to money theydeposit by check takes effect today.   Congress passed the Expedited Funds Availability Act last yearafter consumer groups complained that Americans were losingmillions of dollars a year in lost interest and unjustifiedoverdraft charges because some financial institutions were puttingholds as long as two weeks on funds deposited by check.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market posted scattered losses Wednesday. The DowJones average of 30 industrials finished down 6.58 at 2,031.65.   The dollar rose strongly, particularly against the Japanese yen.   Bond prices posted modest gains in light trading.   Cocoa futures prices tumbled to a 12-year low, pork futures fellsharply, crop futures gained, precious metals rose, energy futuresfell and stock-index futures retreated.</TEXT></DOC>